<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="51" type="etymology">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="51">
<pageBreakToken pageId="2" pageNumber="51" start="start">Etymology</pageBreakToken>
.
</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="51">
The new species is named in honour of its collector, Dr. 
<normalizedToken originalValue="Jindřich">Jindrich</normalizedToken>
<normalizedToken originalValue="Roháček">Rohacek</normalizedToken>
(Silesian Museum, Opava, Czech Republic), a world-famous specialist of 
<taxonomicName family="Anthomyzidae" lsidName="" pageId="2" pageNumber="51" rank="family">Anthomyzidae</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName family="Sphaeroceridae" lsidName="" pageId="2" pageNumber="51" rank="family">Sphaeroceridae</taxonomicName>
(
<taxonomicName lsidName="" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="51" rank="order">Diptera</taxonomicName>
). A noun in genitive singular.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="2" pageNumber="51" type="discussion">
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="51">Discussion.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="2" pageNumber="51">
The new species differs from its similar congeners by details in the structure of the male terminalia, especially its swollen aedeagus and very long aedeagal plate. 
<taxonomicName class="Insecta" family="Limoniidae" genus="Molophilus" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Molophilus (M.) brevihamatus" order="Diptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="51" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="brevihamatus" subGenus="M.">Molophilus (M.) brevihamatus</taxonomicName>
Bangerter, 1947 has a similarly swollen aedeagus, but is distinctive by various other features, including body colouration (brown in 
<taxonomicName genus="M." lsidName="M. (M.) brevihamatus" pageId="2" pageNumber="51" rank="species" species="brevihamatus" subGenus="M.">M. (M.) brevihamatus</taxonomicName>
, shiny black in the new species) and shape of gonostyli and aedeagal plate.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
